    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1950-07-28T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1950-07-28T13:00:00-05:00" n="428"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d428">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00/7–2050: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Embassy in Ireland</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d428fn1">Message drafted by Wayne G. Jackson of the Office
                        of British Commonwealth and Northern European Affairs and cleared by Miriam
                        Camp of the Office of European Regional Affairs and Elim O’Shaughnessy of
                        the Office of Western European Affairs. It was repeated to <gloss
                            target="#t_HICOG1">HICOG</gloss> Frankfort as 714, to London as
                        507.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1950-07-28T14:00:00-04:00"
                            >July 28, 1950—2 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>19. Re <gloss target="#t_Embtel1">Embtel</gloss> 21 July 20 (rptd Frankfort as
                        2),<note n="2" xml:id="d428fn2">Not printed.</note> Dept notes from London’s
                    report nr 373 of July 20<note n="2" xml:id="d428fn4">Not printed.</note> that
                    item on <gloss target="#t_Min1">Min</gloss>s mtg of Council of <gloss
                        target="#t_EUR1">Eur</gloss> pertains to problem of associating <gloss
                        target="#t_GER1">Ger</gloss> in some matter with Comite of <gloss
                        target="#t_Min1">Min</gloss>s rather than making <gloss target="#t_GER1"
                        >Ger</gloss> full member of Council of <gloss target="#t_EUR1">Eur</gloss>.
                    It is our understanding that <gloss target="#t_GER1">Ger</gloss> probably cld
                    not become full <pb facs="0801" n="777" xml:id="pg_777"/> member until such time
                    as conduct of fon relations is turned over to <gloss target="#t_FedRep1"
                        >FedRep</gloss> by <gloss target="#t_HICOM1">HICOM</gloss>. Meanwhile,
                    however, there is nothing to prevent plan which wld allow <gloss
                        target="#t_GER1">Ger</gloss> to have observer or other informal
                    representation at all or some mtgs of Comite of <gloss target="#t_Min1"
                        >Min</gloss>s and its sub-comites. US of course favors eventual admission
                        <gloss target="#t_GER1">Ger</gloss> as full member Council of <gloss
                        target="#t_EUR1">Eur</gloss> when such membership becomes technically
                    possible. However, since US not member Council we have been most careful not to
                    intervene or to try to influence its org or development. Dept wld not wish
                        MacBride<note n="3" xml:id="d428fn3">Séan MacBride, President, Committee of
                        Ministers, Council of Europe.</note> to purport to express US views.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Acheson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
